If you’re into this kind of stuff, I highly recommend following these lovelies! 🎥 @danieldegnan @scarletinni @flushstudios @denniscahlo @mccraeole @faffyhamirl @meghan_theatre

Reposting this series from @denniscahlo because I love the planning-to-product comparison in filmmaking so much, and I’m really proud of how these promos turned out!

You can see the final promos we did for @screamboxtv @bdisgusting at the link in my bio! 📺🔪

Repost from @denniscahlo
•
I used to be really intimidated by storyboarding. Looking at all those amazing pre productions storyboards from ALIEN to 2001 I felt like I just couldn't hack it. But honestly if you can even just draw a stick figure and know how to achieve a little bit of perspective in a drawing it's totally doable. Now I can't live without them.  I storyboard everything by hand in notebooks. I absolutely love the process. These were the storyboards I made for one of the @screamboxtv @bdisgusting  promos. The end result wasn't exactly the same but that's the beauty of filmmaking. You start with a vision and it may change but at least you have the broad strokes to reference during production. #storyboard #storyboarding #director #filmmaking #filmmakerlife #diyfilmmaking #directorstoryboards #screambox
#bethanywatson #denniscahlo

And NOTE: for those of you worried about Minerva’s safety in a moving car, fear not! She spends 99% of our car travels safely curled up in her carrier, asleep. Her anxiety is highest when her carrier is closed up. She feels most comfortable when she feels in control of her surroundings so, because she’s proven herself to be a relaxed pro traveler who is comfortable in our car, we leave her carrier open so she feels like she can move around if she wants. About every 4 hours or so, she wakes up, stretches, does a lap around the car, and takes herself back into her carrier to sleep again. Dennis caught her on her trip back to the carrier 🖤

No context photo dump 🎄

When I lived in Minneapolis, there was a period of time when I was living in a pretty dangerous area. (For those of you who know the story of me being chased into my building by a stranger, this was at that time.) 

Not feeling safe at home, I’d often spend my non-work hours at the @artsmia. This museum became my second home. I’d wander the exhibits for hours and hours, daydreaming of what it would be like to live in rooms like these. I made friends with a few of the statues and told them my secrets, fears, and wildest hopes. I’d sneak naps in the lounge chairs. 

This was my favorite room to daydream in. It’s a recreation of The Grand Salon from the Hôtel de la Bouëxière. Yesterday, when I took @denniscahlo to the museum to show him my “friends,” he snapped this picture. ♥️

Thank you, @artsmia, for being a haven for so many people needing an oasis. It was good to be back 💖

What’s an unexpected place that you consider a second home?
